# Programmatic SEO pages

Patterns:
- `/finance/mortgage-calculator/new-york`
- `/finance/loan-calculator/california`
- `/health/bmi-calculator/adults`

## Each generated page MUST have
- A unique H1 that includes the city/state/segment name.
- **Localized, unique content** — e.g. that city's median home price, cost of living,
  state tax rate, average salary. Cite the source (US Census, BLS). Pages that are
  near-identical with only a name swapped are thin content; do not ship those.
- The same calculator widget.
- A unique meta title + description (location included).
- ≥3 internal links (to the base tool and to sibling locations).

## Canonical — IMPORTANT
- If the page has genuinely unique localized content, its canonical points to
  **ITSELF**. Self-canonical is what lets Google index it — that is the entire point
  of programmatic SEO.
- Only canonical to the base tool if the page is a true near-duplicate with no
  localized data (and prefer not to create such pages at all).
- NOTE: this intentionally overrides the older project note that said "programmatic
  canonical should point to the main tool" — that would de-index every location page
  and defeat the strategy. Discuss before reverting.
- Add every location page to `sitemap.xml`.

## Data
- Pull from a typed dataset (e.g. `data/locations.ts`), never hardcode numbers inline
  per page. Keep figures current and dated, with the source noted.
- Generate routes via `generateStaticParams`; keep build size in mind for large sets.
